SIMPLE: deprivation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Deprivation
<hw>Dep`ri*va"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>deprivatio</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of depriving,
dispossessing, or bereaving; the act of deposing or divesting of some
dignity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being deprived; privation; loss; want;
bereavement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Eccl. Law)</fld> <def>the taking away from a
clergyman his benefice, or other spiritual promotion or
dignity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Deprivation</xex> may be <xex>a beneficio</xex> or
<xex>ab officio</xex>; the first takes away the living, the last
degrades and deposes from the order.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Deprive</ent>⟦br⟧
